const pageContent = "<div id=\"T4281391803\" page-url=\"menu_web\" class=\"page pinned pinned-top fixed\"><a id=\"menu_web\"></a><div class=\"page-layout\"><div class=\"page-content\"><bodycopy style=\"--fit-height: 10px; --resize-parent-width: 100%;\"><header class=\"header-web\" role=\"banner\">\n  <br>\n  <div class=\"header-web__inner\">\n    <a class=\"header-web__brand\" href=\"#\" rel=\"home-page\">THERE &amp; BACK AGAIN</a>\n\n    <nav aria-label=\"Primary\" class=\"header-web__nav\">\n      <a class=\"header-web__link\" href=\"/chronicles/\" rel=\"history\">CHRONICLES</a>\n      <a class=\"header-web__link\" href=\"/by-region/\" rel=\"history\">BY REGION</a>\n      <a class=\"header-web__link\" href=\"/about-the-traveller/\" rel=\"history\">THE TRAVELLER</a>\n    </nav>\n  </div>\n  <br>\n</header>\n\n<hr class=\"header-rule\"></bodycopy></div></div></div><div style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;\" class=\"pages\"><div id=\"B1679728317\" page-url=\"2-days-in-évora-bones-roman-stones\" class=\"page\"><a id=\"2-days-in-évora-bones-roman-stones\"></a><div class=\"page-layout\"><div class=\"page-content\"><bodycopy style=\"--fit-height: 10px; --resize-parent-width: 100%;\"><!--  POST HERO  -->\n<section class=\"post-hero\">\n  <div class=\"post-route-strip\">\n    <span>Europe</span>&nbsp;· Portugal · Alentejo ·&nbsp;<span>Summer 2024</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <h1 class=\"post-hero-title\"><em>2 Days in Évora:</em><br>\nBones &amp; Roman Stones</h1>\n  <p class=\"post-hero-sub\">A single overnight on the Alentejo plain — two thousand years of empire stacked inside one walled white town, with a chapel of bones at its heart.</p>\n  <div class=\"post-stats\">\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">1</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Night</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">5,000</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Bones</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">~2,000yr</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Roman Temple</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">~A$93</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Overnight</span></div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  OPENING: THE ARRIVAL  -->\n<section class=\"opening-prose\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p class=\"drop-cap\">The bus comes in across the Alentejo, and the Alentejo is the part of Portugal that looks least like the postcard: a vast rolling plain of wheat-gold and cork-oak, baked pale by a sun that does not negotiate, the horizon broken only by the occasional whitewashed farm and the long lines of the cork trees with their trunks stripped red. And then, on a low rise in the middle of all that emptiness, a walled white town with a Roman temple standing at the top of it. This is <strong>Évora</strong> — a place where two thousand years of empire have been stacked inside a single set of walls and left there, and the whole UNESCO-listed centre is small enough to cross on foot in twenty minutes.</p>\n      <p>The traveller has one evening and one morning here, no more — a single overnight wedged between the coast and the Spanish border — and that constraint is not a limitation but the right dose. Évora is not a city you exhaust; it is a town you absorb in one slow loop. An afternoon for the dead and the Romans, a night for the Alentejo table, a morning for the living square, and out on the midday bus toward Spain. The shortness is the point. Évora gives the traveller exactly one of everything — one temple, one cathedral, one chapel of bones, one perfect square — and asks only that each be given its full attention.</p>\n      <p>What it really gives, underneath, is a lesson in time. In one short walk the town lays out Roman, Gothic, Renaissance and baroque side by side, and at its strange dark heart it keeps a chapel built of human bones, with a sentence over the door that the whole place seems to be quietly repeating.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER I  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter I</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Bones</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">An afternoon of empire and memento mori</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>Start with the dead, because Évora does. Behind the plain façade of the <strong>Igreja de São Francisco</strong> is the <strong>Capela dos Ossos</strong> — the Chapel of Bones — a small room whose walls and pillars are entirely lined with the bones and skulls of some five thousand people, monks and townsfolk dug up from the overcrowded medieval cemeteries and arranged, in the seventeenth century, into a deliberate, patterned, faintly beautiful reminder of mortality. Over the entrance runs the famous inscription: <em>Nós ossos que aqui estamos, pelos vossos esperamos</em> — “We bones that are here, for yours we wait.” It is not built to frighten so much as to instruct. The Franciscans wanted the comfortable burghers of Évora to walk in, read the line, and adjust their priorities accordingly. It still works. The traveller comes out quieter than they went in.</p>\n      <p>From there the afternoon climbs through the layers. The <strong>Catedral de Évora</strong> is a great fortress-Gothic cathedral of grey granite, half church and half castle, and worth the climb to its roof for the view back over the white town and the gold plain. And then, at the very top, the <strong>Templo Romano</strong> — the so-called Temple of Diana, fourteen Corinthian columns of granite and marble still standing after nearly two thousand years, the best-preserved Roman temple on the Iberian Peninsula, owing its survival to the centuries it spent walled up as a butcher's shop and slaughterhouse, which is exactly the kind of indignity that saves a thing. To stand among its columns as the sun drops and the granite goes orange is to feel the whole stacked weight of the town's history settle into one quiet square. Roman, then Christian, then dead, then golden in the last light.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <aside class=\"pull\">\n    <p>“We bones that are here, for yours we wait.” It is not built to frighten so much as to instruct.</p>\n  </aside>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER II  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter II</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Morning</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">The living town, and out by the midday bus</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>The night belongs to the Alentejo table, which is one of the great reasons to break the journey here at all. This is the region of <em>porco preto</em> — the black Iberian pig fattened on acorns — of bread-thickened <em>açorda</em> and <em>migas</em>, of sheep's-milk <em>queijo de Évora</em> and the big, sun-soaked red wines that the Alentejo now makes as well as anywhere in the country. At a tiny counter like <strong>Botequim da Mouraria</strong> or a proper table like <strong>Dom Joaquim</strong>, the traveller eats the plain rich food of the plains and drinks the wine grown in the heat outside the walls, and the town that spent the afternoon on death proves entirely committed to life after dark.</p>\n      <p>And then the morning, which is the town simply being a town. The <strong>Praça do Giraldo</strong>, Évora's long arcaded main square with its marble fountain, fills with the ordinary business of coffee and errands; the white lanes radiate off it, the university — one of the oldest in Portugal, Jesuit-founded in the sixteenth century — keeps its tiled classrooms; the great arches of the <strong>Água de Prata aqueduct</strong> stride right into the edge of the old town and have houses built into them. There is just time, before the midday bus, for a coffee in the square and a last slow lap of the lanes. The constraint does its work: one night and one morning is exactly long enough to love Évora and not quite long enough to be done with it, which is the best note on which to leave any small perfect place. The bus pulls out east, toward the Spanish border and Cáceres.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<div class=\"ornament\">· · · ✦ · · ·</div>\n\n<div class=\"beat\">One temple, one cathedral, one chapel of bones, one perfect square — and each given its full attention.</div>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: GETTING THERE  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Getting There &amp; Around</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">Évora · Summer 2024</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">By Bus</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>From Lagos</strong> — across the Alentejo in around <strong>4 hours</strong> (roughly <strong>A$31</strong>); from Lisbon about 1.5 hours. The station is a short walk below the walled centre.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Onward to Cáceres</strong> — about <strong>3.5 hours</strong> (roughly <strong>A$36</strong>), east across the border into Spain.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">In Town &amp; Staying</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">Entirely <strong>on foot</strong> — the walled centre crosses in 20 minutes; the only climb is up to the cathedral and temple.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>HI Évora</strong> (Pousada de Juventude) — simple, central, cheap. Roughly <strong>A$93 for the overnight</strong>.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: SITES & TICKETS  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Sites &amp; Tickets</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">Costs in AUD (€ locked)</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">The Must-Sees</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Capela dos Ossos</strong> (at Igreja de São Francisco) — about <strong>A$10 (€6)</strong>. The one unmissable stop; go early or late to dodge the groups.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Catedral de Évora</strong> — about <strong>A$8 (€4.50)</strong> for cathedral, cloister and rooftop; the roof view is worth it.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Free to Wander</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Templo Romano</strong> — free, always open; best at dusk.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Praça do Giraldo, the aqueduct, the lanes</strong> — free; the university charges a small fee for its tiled halls.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: EATING  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Eating in Évora</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">The Alentejo table</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Where</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Botequim da Mouraria</strong> — a tiny, legendary counter (no reservations, stools only) for Alentejo classics and big regional wines. Arrive early or wait.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Dom Joaquim</strong> — the proper sit-down dinner; refined Alentejo cooking, book ahead.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">What</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Porco preto</strong> (acorn-fed black pork), <em>açorda à alentejana</em>, <em>migas</em>, <em>queijo de Évora</em>, and a sun-heavy Alentejo red. Finish with <em>sericaia</em>.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: TIPS & WATCH-OUTS  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Tips &amp; Watch-outs</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">For the overnight</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">On the Ground</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>One night is the right dose.</strong> An afternoon, an evening and a morning cover Évora properly. Don't over-plan it — the pleasure is the slow loop.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Do the Chapel of Bones early or late.</strong> It's small, and a single tour group fills it.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Save the Roman temple for dusk.</strong> The granite goes gold and the square empties.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>The Alentejo is hot and shadeless in summer.</strong> Walk the centre morning and evening; rest in the heat of the day.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Botequim da Mouraria is tiny and takes no bookings.</strong> Go when it opens, or wait.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  VIATOR TOURS  -->\n<div class=\"tours\">\n  <div class=\"tours-label\">Guided Experiences — Évora &amp; the Alentejo</div>\n  <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Sintra/Evora-Megalithic-Almendres-Cromlech-Menhir-Anta-Grande-do-Zambujeiro-dolmen/d50861-109813P48?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Megaliths</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Almendres Cromlech &amp; Zambujeiro Dolmen Tour</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">Europe's great stone circle, older than Stonehenge, on the plain just west of town — the standout local half-day.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~A$60</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Lisbon/Alentejo-Wine-Region-and-Evora-Day-Trip-from-Lisbon/d538-5550_003?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Wine &amp; Heritage</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Alentejo Wine Region &amp; Évora Day Tour</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">Cork forests, vineyards and the historic centre — the full Alentejo day for the wine and the plains.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">From ~A$190</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<!--  ITINERARY  -->\n<section class=\"itin-block\">\n  <div class=\"itin-inner\">\n    <div class=\"itin-block-title\">Évora — One Overnight at a Glance</div>\n\n    <p class=\"itin-meta\">Shape: <strong>a single night between the coast and the border</strong>.</p>\n    <p class=\"itin-meta\">Stay: <strong>HI Évora, ~A$93</strong>.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-section-head\">Évora — afternoon, evening, morning</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-days\">\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">PM</span>Arrive from Lagos. Capela dos Ossos at São Francisco, the Catedral and its rooftop, the Templo Romano at dusk.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Eve</span>Dinner on the Alentejo: Botequim da Mouraria or Dom Joaquim, a big regional red.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">AM</span>Coffee on the Praça do Giraldo, the aqueduct and the university, a last loop of the white lanes.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Midday</span>The bus east, across the border to Cáceres.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CLOSING REFLECTION  -->\n<section class=\"post-closing\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>Évora is a town that holds two thousand years lightly, in a space you can cross in twenty minutes — Roman columns, a Gothic fortress-church, a chapel of patterned bones, a Renaissance square, all stacked together and all still in casual daily use. And over the door of the chapel hangs the sentence the whole place seems to murmur: the bones are here, and they are waiting for yours. It is a strange, plain, profound thing to carry out of a town, and it travels well — the reminder that the empires and the cathedrals and the careful patterns we make all sit, in the end, on the same white plain under the same indifferent sun.</p>\n      <p>The traveller leaves on the midday bus not quite finished with Évora, which is the right way to leave it. The plain rolls past gold and empty; the white town drops below the horizon with its temple on top; and the road runs east, out of Portugal at last, across the border into the harder, hotter, stonier light of Spain.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<div class=\"beat\">But the road is ever onward.</div>\n\n<!--  FAQ  -->\n<section class=\"faq-block\">\n  <div class=\"faq-inner\">\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">What are the must-see things to do in Évora?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">The Capela dos Ossos (Chapel of Bones) at the Igreja de São Francisco, the fortress-Gothic Catedral de Évora and its rooftop, the Roman Templo Romano, and the arcaded Praça do Giraldo. The whole historic centre is a walkable UNESCO World Heritage Site. Out on the plain, the Almendres Cromlech megaliths are worth a half-day.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">Is one day enough for Évora?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">A single overnight — an afternoon, an evening and a morning — covers the town comfortably. Évora's centre is small and walkable; one night lets you see the monuments, eat a proper Alentejo dinner, and absorb the square without rushing. Add a second night only for the megaliths and wine country.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">What is the Chapel of Bones in Évora?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">The Capela dos Ossos is a 17th-century chapel whose walls and pillars are lined with the bones of around 5,000 people, built by Franciscan monks as a meditation on mortality. The inscription over the door reads “We bones that are here, for yours we wait.” It costs about €6 and is Évora's most famous sight.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">How do you get to Évora?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">By bus or train. From Lisbon it's about 1.5 hours; the trip arrived from Lagos on the Algarve coast (around 4 hours) and continued east to Cáceres in Spain. The station is a short walk below the walled old town, which is best explored entirely on foot.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">What should you eat in Évora?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Alentejo cooking: porco preto (acorn-fed black pork), açorda and migas (bread-based dishes), sheep's-milk queijo de Évora, and the region's big sun-soaked red wines. Botequim da Mouraria is a tiny local institution; Dom Joaquim a fine sit-down dinner.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n\n\n<!--  FURTHER READING  -->\n<section class=\"next-chronicles\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-bottom: 2.5rem;\"><em>Further</em> Reading</h2>\n    <div class=\"posts-grid\">\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/2-days-in-c%C3%A1ceres-a-medieval-city-held-in-amber/\" rel=\"history\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Spain · Extremadura</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Cáceres: A Medieval City Held in Amber</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">East across the border — a walled old town so intact it doubles as a film set for Westeros.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">2 days&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;City Guide</div>\n      </a>\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/4-days-in-lagos-the-coast-of-golden-cliffs/\" rel=\"history\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Portugal · Algarve</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Lagos: The Coast of Golden Cliffs</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The coast before the plain — ochre cliffs at dawn and the land running out at Cabo de São Vicente.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">4 days&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;City Guide</div>\n      </a>\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/4-weeks-portugal-to-spain-by-rail-road/\" rel=\"history\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Iberia · Circuit</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Portugal to Spain by Rail and Road</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The full thirty-day circuit — Porto to Barcelona, almost entirely overland, with the costs laid bare.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">4 weeks&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Chronicle</div>\n      </a>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section></bodycopy></div></div></div></div>";
